# A really fancy way of outputting the string "@\n"
true { 0xffffffffffffffff } ! { 0 } ++ { 1 } ++ { 2 }
copy copy copy { 2 2 2 2 } * { 2 2 4 } * { 2 8 }
copy copy { 2 8 8 8 }
* { 2 8 64 } put { 2 8 }
+ { 10 } put { }

# A less fancy way of doing the same thing
64 10 swap { 10 64 } put put

# Some space
endl

# Dynamic invocation of "list-words"
next-token list-words look-up invoke

# Static invocation
list-words
